condition ? value if true : value if false

If apples are red, print Apples are $1. Otherwise, apples are $3.
(apples === "red") ? appleValue = $1 : appleValue = $3

If person is 18 or older, they can get into he club. Otherwise, they cannot.
(person.age >= 18) ? accessClub = true : accessClub = false

If the form has been submitted, render a paragraph saying that your
message has been sent.
Otherwise, render a name input and a submit button.
(submitted is true) ? "Your message has been sent" : render input and button

(submitted === true) ?
(<p> Your message has been sent! </p>) :
(<input type="text" placeholder="Enter your name"></input>
<button type="submit">Submit</button>)

If my array of visitors is greater than 10, render a message saying that the
club is at max capacity. Otherwise, render a button that allows visitors
to go in.
(visitors.length > 10) ? (<p>The club is at max capacity!</p>) :
<button>Come in</button>

If my grocery list contains "apples", render a ordered list. Otherwise, render
an unordered list.

HINT: USE ARRAY METHODS. Check out lodash if necessary.

const groceryList = ["bananas", "oranges", "milk", "apples"];
groceryList.includes("apples") ? (
<ol>
{groceryList.map((item) => {
<li>{item}</li>
})}
</ol>
) : (
<ul>
{groceryList.map((item) => {
<li>{item}</li>
})}
</ul>
);
We have a to-do list. If the list contains the word "urgent", you are going to
create a div and inside that div call a JS alert ex alert("Urgent!").
Otherwise, you will list the tasks using
an unordered list.
const tasks = ["urgent", "do the dishes", "feed the dog"];
(tasks.includes("urgent")) ? (<div> {alert("Urgent!")} </div>) :
(<ul>
{tasks.map((task) {
<li>{task}</li>
})}
</ul>)